<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-132-968  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 132 968.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Educational Technology  March 1989 v29 n3 p22(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Preparing teachers for the information age.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bitter, Gary G.; Yohe, Roger L.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Teacher education programs, not in-service programs, are theproper place to train teachers to use technology.andP;  Teachers shouldbe trained to apply technical skills and to understand the limits,extensions and future of technology.andP;  A preservice teachertechnology program must train teachers to be proficient, criticalusers of educational technologies.andP;  Before a college or universityintroduces technology into the curriculum, the administration andthe faculty must be committed to the program.andP;  The first step intechnology training for preservice teachers in technology is anindividualized, skills-based introduction that emphasizes hands-onexperience.andP;  The second step stresses specification integrationtechniques.andP;  The third step is advanced instruction, and the finalstep is continuing education.andP;  Each step must emphasize processesand products, reinforce goals of the program, and includeevaluation and research.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Teacher EducationComputer EducationCurriculumTechnologyColleges and UniversitiesEducation.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   A model for infusing technology into a teacher preparationprogram. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>